---
import Slide from "../components/Slide.astro";
---

<Slide>
	<h2>How does a computer see a body?</h2>
	<div class="columns">
		<div class="pixel-grid" aria-hidden="true">
			{
				[54, 58, 61, 52, 49, 47, 60, 72, 84, 79, 66, 55, 63, 91, 118, 108, 82, 59, 57, 88, 121, 112, 77, 51, 50, 62, 78, 74, 58, 46, 44, 48, 52, 50, 45, 41].map((v) => (
					<span style={`background: rgb(${v + 100} ${v + 60} ${v + 40})`}>{v}</span>
				))
			}
		</div>
		<ul>
			<li class="fragment">To a camera, a frame is <strong>just a grid of numbers</strong> — no “hand”, no “arm”</li>
			<li class="fragment">Classic CV: skin color, edges, contours → brittle</li>
			<li class="fragment">Deep learning: <strong>CNNs learn</strong> what fingers and joints look like</li>
			<li class="fragment">
				Key idea — <strong>landmark detection</strong>: don't classify the image,
				<em>regress the (x,&nbsp;y,&nbsp;z) of each joint</em>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	<aside class="notes">
		The pixel grid is literally what the model receives. The shift from "is there a hand?" (classification) to "where
		is each knuckle?" (regression) is what makes everything in this talk possible.
	</aside>
</Slide>

<style>
	.columns {
		display: flex;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 1em;
		text-align: left;
	}
	ul {
		font-size: 0.75em;
	}
	.pixel-grid {
		flex-shrink: 0;
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(6, 1fr);
		gap: 2px;
		width: 260px;

		span {
			display: grid;
			place-items: center;
			aspect-ratio: 1;
			font-size: 13px;
			font-family: monospace;
			color: rgb(0 0 0 / 0.65);
			border-radius: 2px;
		}
	}
</style>
